IBM history: From cheese slices to space flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a century ago, originally called Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It did not take over the name IBM until 1924 - originally a brand used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The basis for the later IBM was given by the merger of four firms whose history dates back to the eighties of the nineteenth century.
They owned technology such as the famous "sticks," the clock recording the staff's arrival and departure.
The architect of the new firm was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the company's supervisory board until 1930.
Flint hired the head of rival firm, Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed IBM's founder - Watson's ideas are still built on the unbeatable corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all sorts of machines for business - from meat and cheese slices to cash registers.
In the first four years that Watson headed the company, turnover doubled to $9 million and the company's widespread expansion into all continents began.
Watson was so indispensable for the company that after nearly forty years in the chief executive chair, he was succeeded by his son, Thomas Watson Jr.
Under his leadership, IBM began work on the development of artificial intelligence, developing the first programming language.
In the 1960s, people and computers from IBM helped NASA manage space flights to Merkur, Saturn, and, in 1969, the famous human flight to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family - the IBM System/360, series.
The classic "Pécé," which established the computer standard of the time, called the IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, on the contrary, it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and began to devote itself to high-valen value-added consultancy and services.
