How tour prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia at the time: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Travel agencies at the time were overwhelmingly selling only trips to the socialist bloc countries, as travel to the west was very restricted.
Czech tourists thus travelled on holiday to the sea to the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea off the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and Hungary (the Balinathon).
The bright exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when there was a chance to travel to Yugoslavia, but then the Yugoslav regime went to the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were subsequently very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
In case a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to, for example, Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter from this country, otherwise an individual path was not possible.
Travel agents at the time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to queue up overnight with a sleeping bag or have "good acquaintances" in the travel agency.
Even so, it was not won.
The so-called foreign exchange pledge, which was a condition for travel to the West, was not given to "politically unreliable people" who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency, so without a foreign exchange promise it was not possible to raise funds (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
However, the most often Czechs vacationed in the Czech Republic, resulting in a large number of cottages that Czechs acquired and this custom is still alive today.
Travel by the Czechs has thus experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in the countries around the world.
The huge paradox, which we are no longer aware of today, is that it was not possible to travel freely to us in the most popular Croatia for us at the moment, as it was part of what was then Yugoslavia.
Early in the 1990s, the visa requirement was lifted to neighbouring Western European countries, triggering a huge wave of short-term visits to Vienna and Germany, in particular.
For a long time the Czechoslovaks could not get enough trips to the West, everyone wanted to at least take a look for a while.
In Paris, for example, tours of Czechs in parks in tents slept, as our income at the time did not allow us to pay for a hotel or a guesthouse.
A typical feature of Czechs' travel at this time was to drive their own food, canned, salami, etc. to save money.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, which our tourists were finally able to buy the Western currency freely after many weeks of flight.
However, our standard of living, and with it, average salaries have risen, resulting in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agents have regularly started to prepare tours with charter air links since 1997, making air tours incredibly cheaper to contract volume discounts compared to the past.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs already had visa-free travel to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the US, which continued to make our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel came as soon as 2000, when thanks to considerable demand, the first direct charter flight to exotica was dispatched from the Czech Republic, it was to Thailand.
From this year onwards, direct charters fly out with Czech tourists to warm far-off countries, this winter will be flown directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visited by around 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US revoked visas for Czech tourists, and thus our country was finally among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, for the first time in history, Czechs also spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and spent more than 15,000 on one foreign holiday for the first time in their history, including the cost of the whereabouts. CZK per person.
