Once data from 500 to 600 children have been obtained, the study will continue at the Independencia Sports Center (south of the Federal District) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Center).
He explained that the aim of this research was to identify the ingredients and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity and to trace to Mexican children and young people the risk factors and thus prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Diabetes Day, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim was to collect data from 3,000 children and young people between the age of 3,000 and 14, with the consent and supervised of parents, to apply specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about the physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He specified that every Saturday, all participants are being given anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure is measured, glucose, triglicernides, cholesterol, insulin are determined and genes are studied (they are trying to identify the genes involved in childhood obesity).
Cruz López said this research reflected the concern of health professionals over the alarming increase in child's weight.
'Health polls conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, there was an increase in obesity in the boys by 77% and for girls by 47%. There was also a dramatic increase in the case of overweight', said the IMSS expert.
He said that one of the reasons for the search for indicators was the assumption that the country's population was different from that of other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican has 65% of Indian-American genetic make-up, 30% European and 5% African. This is reflected in the genes responsible for the emergence of diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity are commonly explained as an inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefits of the participants were to receive an overall assessment of the condition of the children, thus determining whether they show any known overweight or obesity.
He said that even the presence of dark-coloured wrinkles (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicated the likelihood that the individual would suffer from metabolic problems and pre-curklar conditions.
The information is still confidential, with doctors passing it in writing to their parents and explaining to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they have to make to avoid the disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three major ingredients that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle that means a lack of daily physical activity, a day's sitting in front of the TV, and the use of means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Overweight is also due to a large caloric intake, i.e. greater consumption of sweetened beverages, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content, and the genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
In Asphalt from UNAM there will be no potholes
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty of UNAM, creates modified asphalts with polymers to create a mixture with better functionality, independent of climatic conditions and temperature
If the cobbles were properly cared for, there would be no need to repair nearly 200,000 potholes after each rainy season in the Metropolitan area of Valle de México, Rafael Herrera hijacker, a scientist at the Chemical Faculty (FQ) at the UNAM, who also added that if the design and maintenance of asphalt paving were adequate, there would be a significant reduction in potholes, or even be able to be removed altogether.
In his lecture, the Technology Cue of Colour, he delivered in the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his direction was developing modified polymer asphalt asphalt, creating a mixture with similar characteristics to the asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Nájer believes that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places with extremely warm climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of the crude oil, is a cluster of hydrocarbon molecules, moocclescopic molecules called asphaltes, and other low molecular weights called mortars. Together, they give the asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The viscole-easterty nature of asphalt is that at high temperatures, around 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, has a high viscosity at 120 degrees and is almost in firm state at 50 degrees, while at low temperatures, asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperatures, the chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A scientist at the Chemistry School observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible paving, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers are asphalt insert, made up of small stones, then compressed in the asphalt.
He stressed that every stone that forms the liner is topped with asphalt.
When passing cars or when pressuring, it is thus possible to disinherit the forces in the pavement well.
If it was modified asphalt, they would break up even better, the chemical engineer believes.
He added that the asphalt insert would be the last layer called the cloak, made up of fine rock, i.e. sand also encased in asphalts.
As this layer will come into contact with the vehicle rims, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt insert and must ensure the friction of the road.
As part of the cobbles, it will be subjected to heavy loads, the casing must be of sufficient thickness and care about the material from which it is made.
The climate, especially the humidity and the temperature changes, are also a very important factor to be remembered. Water in particular has a major impact on the functionality of the asphalt insert.
Once the terrain is damp, the water travels inwards and it is difficult to get out, this causes all layers of pavement to be softened and thus the formation of potholes.
He explained that the film of the cladding was the first to be damaged during the potholes' creation, and only then did the asphalt insert be damaged. However, the damage does not occur at one point, but it is a gradual process that should be stopped at the first stamps using appropriate maintenance programmes.
As a member of the National Researchers System, he also explained that the load on vehicles is another important factor in creating potholes, and therefore the thickness of each individual layer of paving must be commensurate with the load of vehicles and it must be guaranteed that this burden will not be exceeded. Only in this way can we prevent the frequent emergence of potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that there is still a lot of work to do when it comes to asphalt, and the research is at the beginning. It is worth mentioning, for example, asphalt emulsions, which are already available on the market in other countries and make it easy to repair potholes without having to use high temperatures.
